Completed questions 190–200 with detailed notes, definitions, and mistake review. Topics included certificate trust issues, honeypots, tabletop exercises, certificate revocation lists (CRL), acceptable use policies (AUP), data sovereignty, web application protections, SIEM in cloud environments, malicious updates, and privileged access management (PAM).

Topics Reviewed
Certificate Trust & PKI

Certificates must be issued by a trusted Certificate Authority (CA).

Self-signed certificates can trigger security warnings due to lack of trust validation.

CRL (Certificate Revocation List)

Lists certificates that are no longer trusted.

Ensures compromised or revoked certificates are not accepted.

Deception Technologies

Honeypots

Decoy systems designed to attract attackers.

Provide insight into attacker behavior without risking real systems.

Incident Response Preparedness

Tabletop Exercises

Scenario-based discussions used to simulate incidents.

Improve coordination, communication, and readiness of response teams.

Security Policies

AUP (Acceptable Use Policy)

Defines proper and improper use of organizational systems.

Sets behavioral expectations for users.

Data Governance

Data Sovereignty

Data is subject to the laws of the country where it is stored.

Important for compliance and regulatory requirements.

Web Application Security

Protection strategies include:

Regular patching and updates

Web Application Firewalls (WAF)

Helps defend against attacks such as injection and exploitation.

Security Monitoring (Cloud)

SIEM

Centralized logging and monitoring across cloud and on-prem systems

Provides real-time alerts and analysis of security events

Supply Chain / Update Risks

Malicious Updates

Attackers may compromise software updates to gain access.

Requires validation and integrity checking of updates.

Privileged Access Security

PAM (Privileged Access Management)

Controls access to high-level accounts

Includes:

Session monitoring

Access control enforcement

Ensures secure fallback access if SSO fails

